Temperatures tonight are expected to fall to at or below freezing for all of South Central Texas beginning around midnight on the Plateau and Hill Country and during the overnight hours for locations along and east of the Interstate 35 corridor. With the exception of areas south of Interstate 10 and east of Interstate 37 where some flurries may occur, precipitation is expected to mostly diminish before the freezing temperatures return late tonight so no additional accumulating snowfall is expected. However, with the extensive rainfall over the area the last couple days, any remnant wet areas may freeze tonight resulting in dangerous black ice conditions, especially on bridges, overpasses, and some secondary roadways. As colder air moves into central Indiana this afternoon behind a cold front, scattered snow showers and squalls will continue to develop across the area. The focus for the heavier snow showers and squalls will generally be along and east of Interstate 65. The squalls will create rapidly changing conditions over short distances as burst of heavier snow cause drastic reductions in visibility. Wind gusts up to 30 mph may cause blowing snow as well within heavier squalls. Snow showers and squalls will end this evening with additional accumulations up to an inch, especially over northeast portions of central Indiana. Motorists traveling into this evening should be alert to rapidly changing road conditions and reduce their speed when encountering heavier snow showers and squalls.
